WEBVTT

00:01.293 --> 00:03.128
[hammer striking metal]

00:06.131 --> 00:09.343
<i>[intense music]</i>

00:09.343 --> 00:11.929
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:11.929 --> 00:14.890
<i>[strutting rock music]</i>

00:14.890 --> 00:18.644
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:18.644 --> 00:19.728
<i>‐ My name's Colton Arias.</i>

00:19.728 --> 00:20.896
<i>I'm 18 years old.</i>

00:20.896 --> 00:22.606
I really love making something

00:22.606 --> 00:23.941
that's gonna last

00:23.941 --> 00:26.193
<i>for a really long time.</i>

00:26.193 --> 00:28.111
And it's also really fun

00:28.111 --> 00:30.572
to hit stuff on fire.

00:30.572 --> 00:31.907
<i>‐ My name is Bryce Perez.</i>

00:31.907 --> 00:33.283
<i>I'm 21 years old.</i>

00:33.283 --> 00:36.245
I just enlisted
in the United States Air Force.

00:36.245 --> 00:39.039
It's actually one of my dreams
to be on "Forged in Fire,"

00:39.039 --> 00:40.582
and the fact that
I get to do it

00:40.582 --> 00:43.877
two weeks out from joining
the military is amazing to me.

00:43.877 --> 00:45.212
<i>It really is.</i>

00:45.212 --> 00:46.547
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:46.547 --> 00:47.881
<i>‐ My name's Grant Saxman.</i>

00:47.881 --> 00:49.132
A lot of times when I first

00:49.132 --> 00:51.134
tell people that
I'm a blacksmith,

00:51.134 --> 00:52.970
they just kind of brush it off
as a hobby, you know.

00:52.970 --> 00:54.763
<i>And then when I start</i>
<i>to show 'em</i>

00:54.763 --> 00:56.640
<i>the things</i>
<i>that I actually can do,</i>

00:56.640 --> 00:59.476
then suddenly it's, "Wow."

00:59.476 --> 01:00.477
<i>‐ I'm Craig Miller.</i>

01:00.477 --> 01:02.437
I've been working with my hands

01:02.437 --> 01:03.814
for my entire life.

01:03.814 --> 01:05.524
<i>I make everything.</i>

01:05.524 --> 01:07.276
<i>I've built my own cameras.</i>

01:07.276 --> 01:09.987
I built a vending machine
when I was five years old.

01:09.987 --> 01:13.699
So this is just the next step
along the line.

01:13.699 --> 01:15.158
<i>[brooding music]</i>

01:15.158 --> 01:17.661
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:17.661 --> 01:18.829
You're here to engage

01:18.829 --> 01:19.997
in three rounds of timed

01:19.997 --> 01:21.415
edged‐weapon‐making competition

01:21.415 --> 01:23.250
designed to test every aspect
of your skills

01:23.250 --> 01:24.751
in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:24.751 --> 01:26.044
who will tell us which of you

01:26.044 --> 01:27.462
is the next "Forged in Fire"
champion

01:27.462 --> 01:30.549
leaving this forge with a check
for $10,000.

01:30.549 --> 01:32.175
Let's meet your judges now.

01:32.175 --> 01:35.637
Up first: ABS Master Smith
J. Neilson.

01:35.637 --> 01:37.764
Next, Historic Weapons
Re‐creation Specialist,

01:37.764 --> 01:39.016
David Baker.

01:39.016 --> 01:42.978
Last, Edged Weapons Specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:42.978 --> 01:44.479
Gentlemen, in every single one

01:44.479 --> 01:45.939
of these competitions,

01:45.939 --> 01:48.317
we have four bladesmiths
walk through that door,

01:48.317 --> 01:50.444
but oftentimes,
there's the presence

01:50.444 --> 01:53.155
of a fifth, unnamed bladesmith.

01:53.155 --> 01:56.325
<i>[metallic drumming]</i>

01:56.325 --> 01:57.909
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:57.909 --> 02:00.329
Big Blu.

02:00.329 --> 02:01.580
<i>‐ What on Earth are</i>
<i>we gonna do</i>

02:01.580 --> 02:03.957
with this giant piece of history
right here?

02:03.957 --> 02:05.584
‐ This big blue power hammer

02:05.584 --> 02:07.044
has facilitated the success

02:07.044 --> 02:10.130
of almost every single
"Forged in Fire" champion

02:10.130 --> 02:11.673
that's walked through
that door.

02:11.673 --> 02:13.050
On the other hand,

02:13.050 --> 02:15.802
it has literally chewed up
and spit out

02:15.802 --> 02:18.555
the dreams
of other bladesmiths...

02:18.555 --> 02:20.557
‐ <i>Oh, man!</i>

02:20.557 --> 02:22.517
‐ Turning their forge experience

02:22.517 --> 02:23.852
into an absolute nightmare.

02:23.852 --> 02:24.978
<i>[maniacal laughing]</i>

02:24.978 --> 02:26.480
Well, now it's time to replace

02:26.480 --> 02:28.523
and retire Big Blu,

02:28.523 --> 02:30.859
but not before we rip out
its beating heart

02:30.859 --> 02:32.694
and turn that high‐carbon piston

02:32.694 --> 02:35.072
into four competition choppers

02:35.072 --> 02:38.158
<i>that fall between 11</i>
<i>and 13 inches in length.</i>

02:38.158 --> 02:39.910
<i>Your blades at the end</i>
<i>of this round</i>

02:39.910 --> 02:42.954
<i>must not exceed</i>
<i>22 inches overall.</i>

02:42.954 --> 02:45.040
<i>‐ I've never had</i>
<i>a power hammer before,</i>

02:45.040 --> 02:46.541
<i>but I've always wanted one,</i>

02:46.541 --> 02:48.085
so seeing a really nice one

02:48.085 --> 02:49.920
getting torn apart‐‐

02:49.920 --> 02:51.880
<i>it just hurts me.</i>

02:51.880 --> 02:53.173
‐ You will have just three hours

02:53.173 --> 02:55.050
in which to complete
all your work.

02:55.050 --> 02:56.510
If you make it
to the second round,

02:56.510 --> 02:57.886
you'll be given a chance

02:57.886 --> 03:00.097
to turn those blades
into fully functional weapons

03:00.097 --> 03:02.349
by attaching handles to them
so that we can test them

03:02.349 --> 03:05.435
for strength and durability
in a bamboo chop

03:05.435 --> 03:09.356
and for edge retention
in a rope bridge slice.

03:09.356 --> 03:10.440
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:10.440 --> 03:12.109
Your time starts now.

03:12.109 --> 03:13.568
<i>[energetic rock music]</i>

03:13.568 --> 03:15.070
‐ So long, Big Blu.

03:15.070 --> 03:17.114
‐ Yeah, I know.
I just got so upset.

03:17.114 --> 03:18.365
I wanted that in my shop!

03:18.365 --> 03:20.200
‐ I'll get‐‐
‐ Wrench? Wrenches?

03:20.200 --> 03:22.244
<i>‐ We've put this machine</i>
<i>through its paces.</i>

03:22.244 --> 03:25.956
<i>We've had this machine running</i>
<i>non‐stop for four years.</i>

03:25.956 --> 03:27.207
‐ It's hard to watch.

03:27.207 --> 03:28.583
‐ I'll get the ladder.

03:28.583 --> 03:29.918
‐ So these guys are tasked

03:29.918 --> 03:32.587
with pulling the piston
out of this Big Blu.

03:32.587 --> 03:34.381
Now, we've already replaced it,

03:34.381 --> 03:37.551
and this one is sacrificing
that piston

03:37.551 --> 03:39.136
to our bladesmiths.

03:39.136 --> 03:41.680
‐ We only have three hours
to take the thing apart

03:41.680 --> 03:42.681
and make a knife?

03:42.681 --> 03:43.890
<i>That's insane.</i>

03:43.890 --> 03:45.642
‐ What kind of steel
is that piston?

03:45.642 --> 03:47.102
‐ W2.

03:47.102 --> 03:49.563
‐ We all just decide
that we're gonna work together

03:49.563 --> 03:50.647
to take this thing apart.

03:50.647 --> 03:51.857
<i>It'll benefit all of us.</i>

03:51.857 --> 03:53.233
‐ That's really a testament

03:53.233 --> 03:55.777
to the competitorship
that we have out here...

03:55.777 --> 03:57.654
‐ We're coming, she's going!

03:57.654 --> 03:59.948
‐ When you watch these guys
help one another

03:59.948 --> 04:02.617
disassemble that machine
very quickly.

04:02.617 --> 04:05.328
‐ We know we're all working
off the same piece of steel.

04:05.328 --> 04:07.414
<i>There's no working</i>
<i>against each other.</i>

04:07.414 --> 04:08.748
<i>We gotta get this thing off.</i>

04:08.748 --> 04:10.792
‐ We're cannibalizing Big Blu.

04:10.792 --> 04:12.294
Like, what's next, J.?

04:12.294 --> 04:14.546
‐ Cannibalize us.
‐ Exactly!

04:14.546 --> 04:15.755
‐ Up!
‐ Got it?

04:15.755 --> 04:16.798
‐ Down!

04:16.798 --> 04:18.133
‐ A lot of steel there.

04:18.133 --> 04:20.385
It'll be plenty for us
to work with.

04:20.385 --> 04:22.512
‐ So this is W2
high‐carbon steel.

04:22.512 --> 04:26.099
What are the specific properties
of W2 steel?

04:26.099 --> 04:29.060
‐ It's just got
a little more compounds than W1.

04:29.060 --> 04:30.854
But it's good, tough steel.
It moves well.

04:30.854 --> 04:31.980
It's a good forgeable steel.

04:31.980 --> 04:33.190
‐ Nice.
‐ Nice!

04:33.190 --> 04:34.149
‐ Nice, nice.

04:34.149 --> 04:35.484
‐ You got one guy in a sportie

04:35.484 --> 04:36.651
who's doing the work.

04:36.651 --> 04:38.403
‐ It's almost like shop class,

04:38.403 --> 04:40.030
these young kids
and their shop class teacher.

04:40.030 --> 04:41.656
They're all in one spot.

04:41.656 --> 04:44.451
[grinding]

04:44.451 --> 04:46.536
<i>‐ We all have an even amount</i>
<i>of steel</i>

04:46.536 --> 04:48.830
to make a knife
to meet parameters.

04:48.830 --> 04:52.083
‐ That's about
a 1 3/8 inch shaft.

04:52.083 --> 04:55.003
Each smith's gonna get
maybe 4 1/2 inches of metal.

04:55.003 --> 04:56.338
‐ Not bad.

04:56.338 --> 04:58.465
‐ That's not a lot to make
a 12‐inch chopper.

04:58.465 --> 04:59.800
‐ No, you gotta be careful.

04:59.800 --> 05:01.176
We tell these guys
all the time,

05:01.176 --> 05:03.011
"We don't want boat anchors."

05:03.011 --> 05:04.179
It doesn't have to be

05:04.179 --> 05:05.555
a big, heavy, thick knife
to be strong.

05:05.555 --> 05:07.974
All they have to do
is nail the heat‐treat.

05:07.974 --> 05:10.310
<i>‐ When the steel finally</i>
<i>gets up to temperature,</i>

05:10.310 --> 05:12.562
I start squishing
the steel down.

05:12.562 --> 05:13.980
<i>I'm pretty optimistic</i>

05:13.980 --> 05:16.191
<i>about how fast I can get</i>
<i>this thing drawn out.</i>

05:16.191 --> 05:19.486
I just purchased a press
about a week ago.

05:19.486 --> 05:21.530
<i>So I have a little bit</i>
<i>of experience,</i>

05:21.530 --> 05:23.156
but up until that point,

05:23.156 --> 05:25.325
I basically just depended

05:25.325 --> 05:26.701
on these guys right here.

05:26.701 --> 05:28.662
<i>[energetic punk rock music]</i>

05:28.662 --> 05:31.414
‐ We've got Grant heading over
to new blue.

05:31.414 --> 05:33.250
‐ Nice having a brand‐new
Big Blu in here.

05:33.250 --> 05:34.960
That things hits with a ton
of pressure,

05:34.960 --> 05:36.419
and it's really dialed in.

05:36.419 --> 05:37.963
<i>‐ The power hammer?</i>

05:37.963 --> 05:39.339
So incredible.

05:39.339 --> 05:40.924
<i>Super‐fast machine.</i>

05:40.924 --> 05:43.343
<i>I am drawing out that material</i>

05:43.343 --> 05:46.263
much faster than I thought
I would be able to.

05:46.263 --> 05:47.973
<i>‐ Thinking of all the history</i>

05:47.973 --> 05:50.058
that this machine's been
through in "Forged in Fire,"

05:50.058 --> 05:51.518
<i>and I just want to produce</i>
<i>a knife</i>

05:51.518 --> 05:53.854
that is worthy of Big Blu.

05:53.854 --> 05:55.647
‐ This is the equivalent
of making, like,

05:55.647 --> 05:57.899
a bone‐handled knife
out of my femur.

05:57.899 --> 05:59.234
‐ Exactly what I was thinking!

05:59.234 --> 06:01.653
It's like watching chicken
dipped in egg batter.

06:01.653 --> 06:04.197
You're working on yourself!

06:04.197 --> 06:06.199
‐ Using Big Blu to make a knife
out of Big Blu

06:06.199 --> 06:08.285
didn't really cross my mind.

06:08.285 --> 06:11.371
<i>On the whole, my progress</i>
<i>is doing really well,</i>

06:11.371 --> 06:14.916
but I'm definitely the old guy
in the room.

06:14.916 --> 06:17.294
<i>It's me against</i>
<i>three younger guys</i>

06:17.294 --> 06:20.130
that are probably a little more
physically fit than me,

06:20.130 --> 06:23.133
but maybe I'm a little more
mentally fit than them.

06:23.133 --> 06:24.801
‐ One hour has elapsed!

06:24.801 --> 06:27.721
You have two hours remaining
to finish your work.

06:27.721 --> 06:29.556
‐ I realize after
about two passes

06:29.556 --> 06:31.057
through Big Blu,
I'm spending too much time

06:31.057 --> 06:32.726
<i>on Big Blu itself.</i>

06:32.726 --> 06:34.728
I'm not letting my metal
heat up as fast.

06:34.728 --> 06:36.354
<i>So time is just ticking by</i>

06:36.354 --> 06:38.148
<i>because I'm not really</i>
<i>moving metal.</i>

06:38.148 --> 06:41.443
‐ It looks like Bryce has some,
maybe different thicknesses

06:41.443 --> 06:42.777
on his blade.

06:42.777 --> 06:44.613
You can see that there
are dark spots,

06:44.613 --> 06:46.156
and then there are spots

06:46.156 --> 06:47.824
that are holding
a little bit more heat.

06:47.824 --> 06:50.493
‐ It's sitting
under the actual burners,

06:50.493 --> 06:54.581
and he's not moving that steel
back and forth, evening it out.

06:54.581 --> 06:57.626
<i>[heavy metal bassline]</i>

06:57.626 --> 06:59.419
‐ Once I get the flat billet
drawn out

06:59.419 --> 07:01.671
to the correct dimensions,

07:01.671 --> 07:05.842
<i>I start trying to forge in</i>
<i>the rough profile.</i>

07:05.842 --> 07:08.470
I had been pacing myself
up to this point,

07:08.470 --> 07:10.930
so I don't gas out.

07:10.930 --> 07:13.183
<i>I could take this over</i>
<i>to Big Blu,</i>

07:13.183 --> 07:14.601
do it a lot quicker,

07:14.601 --> 07:15.852
but I'm trying to stick
to what I know

07:15.852 --> 07:17.103
<i>so I don't end up</i>

07:17.103 --> 07:18.688
<i>messing something up</i>
<i>permanently.</i>

07:18.688 --> 07:20.231
‐ What kind of shapes
do we expect to see

07:20.231 --> 07:22.359
when we say
"competition chopper?"

07:22.359 --> 07:24.194
‐ I'm not expecting to see
a tip on it.

07:24.194 --> 07:25.820
<i>We're not doing</i>
<i>any stabbing tests,</i>

07:25.820 --> 07:27.739
<i>so what's the point</i>
<i>of working a tip into it?</i>

07:27.739 --> 07:29.991
Just drop it down from the front
and focus on the edge.

07:29.991 --> 07:33.036
Make it high; that way you get
a nice steep edge geometry

07:33.036 --> 07:34.287
<i>with your bevels coming down.</i>

07:34.287 --> 07:35.705
<i>A good slicer.</i>

07:35.705 --> 07:36.956
It's a simple knife.

07:36.956 --> 07:38.500
It's kind of like giving
a master chef an egg

07:38.500 --> 07:41.086
and seeing how awesome
he can make it.

07:41.086 --> 07:43.838
<i>‐ I just forge it down</i>
<i>to a small angle</i>

07:43.838 --> 07:46.091
and then start work
on the bevel.

07:46.091 --> 07:47.550
<i>[hard rock guitar riff]</i>

07:47.550 --> 07:49.552
<i>‐ After I get profiling done,</i>

07:49.552 --> 07:51.304
I get ready to drill some holes

07:51.304 --> 07:53.306
for the pins in the next round.

07:53.306 --> 07:55.850
‐ Colton is over here
using a punch

07:55.850 --> 07:59.062
to kind of mark some holes
for his tang.

07:59.062 --> 08:00.939
‐ That's smart work.

08:00.939 --> 08:03.900
‐ I do this now,
because in the next round,

08:03.900 --> 08:06.069
<i>it will be quenched and hard</i>

08:06.069 --> 08:08.822
and sometimes
you can't drill holes

08:08.822 --> 08:10.031
in hardened steel.

08:10.031 --> 08:11.616
‐ The blades are coming along.

08:11.616 --> 08:14.411
We should have some beautiful
competition choppers

08:14.411 --> 08:17.706
in the next hour or so.

08:17.706 --> 08:19.541
‐ Right now I'm just gonna go
grinding the handle

08:19.541 --> 08:21.501
a little bit more,
tweak it,

08:21.501 --> 08:23.211
shorten it up
and it will be good,

08:23.211 --> 08:25.338
so I can quench it.

08:25.338 --> 08:26.881
<i>I'm thinking, "Wow,</i>

08:26.881 --> 08:30.135
I have never used a grinder
like this before."

08:30.135 --> 08:31.845
This shop, compared to mine,

08:31.845 --> 08:33.972
blows mine out of the water.

08:33.972 --> 08:36.850
It feels a little odd
using other people's tools,

08:36.850 --> 08:40.270
but you just gotta
roll with the punches.

08:40.270 --> 08:42.230
<i>[strutting rock riff]</i>

08:42.230 --> 08:43.898
<i>‐ So I'm working on Big Blu.</i>

08:43.898 --> 08:45.442
I'm trying to get my billet
drawn out

08:45.442 --> 08:46.568
to a length where I know

08:46.568 --> 08:48.319
it's gonna fit requirements,

08:48.319 --> 08:49.446
<i>and as I'm doing that,</i>

08:49.446 --> 08:50.864
<i>I kind of lost sight of where</i>

08:50.864 --> 08:52.407
my handle was gonna start

08:52.407 --> 08:53.992
<i>and where my blade</i>
<i>was gonna start.</i>

08:53.992 --> 08:55.577
<i>And that junction is where</i>

08:55.577 --> 08:57.954
I kind of let it get
a little too thin.

08:57.954 --> 09:00.498
That's gonna probably
do me right there.

09:00.498 --> 09:02.959
My only options are either
to fold it and forge‐weld it,

09:02.959 --> 09:04.294
which I really don't
want to do,

09:04.294 --> 09:07.338
<i>or make sure that I take care</i>
<i>of this now,</i>

09:07.338 --> 09:09.758
<i>while it's still</i>
<i>a manageable problem.</i>

09:09.758 --> 09:11.092
‐ Could be an issue.

09:11.092 --> 09:12.427
‐ The junction of the handle

09:12.427 --> 09:14.012
is where all of the shock
is gonna go.

09:14.012 --> 09:16.389
<i>Basically, I've gotta turn</i>
<i>my billet around</i>

09:16.389 --> 09:19.434
<i>and I need to allow</i>
<i>the thin spot to be the tip</i>

09:19.434 --> 09:21.269
where it may be a hair thinner

09:21.269 --> 09:23.188
<i>and draw out the tang</i>
<i>on the other side.</i>

09:23.188 --> 09:24.939
[metallic tinks]

09:24.939 --> 09:27.942
‐ So over here, it looks like
Bryce has switched over

09:27.942 --> 09:30.487
to the one inch contact wheel.

09:30.487 --> 09:31.821
‐ I'm camped out at the grinder

09:31.821 --> 09:34.074
for what feels like maybe
a whole hour,

09:34.074 --> 09:36.076
<i>and finally I realize,</i>
<i>"Oh crap,</i>

09:36.076 --> 09:38.787
<i>I gotta get this thing</i>
<i>to the heat‐treat!"</i>

09:38.787 --> 09:40.205
<i>Before I heat‐treat,</i>

09:40.205 --> 09:42.540
I definitely am thermocycling
that blade.

09:42.540 --> 09:44.209
Now I gotta make sure
there's not gonna be

09:44.209 --> 09:45.877
any cracking or tinging
or warps

09:45.877 --> 09:47.003
<i>when I put it in that oil.</i>

09:47.003 --> 09:49.214
Quenching!

09:49.214 --> 09:50.590
‐ Quenching?
‐ Not bad.

09:50.590 --> 09:51.800
That was a good color.

09:51.800 --> 09:53.593
‐ Good job.
Look at that.

09:53.593 --> 09:55.428
Looks pretty straight from here.

09:55.428 --> 09:57.055
<i>‐ It looks amazing.</i>

09:57.055 --> 10:00.266
I'm pumped right now.
Let's go.

10:00.266 --> 10:01.601
<i>[hard rock riff]</i>

10:01.601 --> 10:03.353
‐ I'm just looking at my blade

10:03.353 --> 10:05.647
and I'm not very happy with it.

10:05.647 --> 10:07.607
<i>There's a notch on the back</i>

10:07.607 --> 10:09.109
<i>where I missed forging it out,</i>

10:09.109 --> 10:10.610
<i>and I wasn't able</i>
<i>to grind it down.</i>

10:10.610 --> 10:12.654
The plunge line is really messy
right now,

10:12.654 --> 10:15.448
<i>and the handle itself</i>
<i>is pretty bulky.</i>

10:15.448 --> 10:17.200
I know exactly
what I have to do,

10:17.200 --> 10:19.244
<i>so I'm going to quench.</i>

10:19.244 --> 10:21.079
[hissing]

10:21.079 --> 10:22.747
‐ Grant is into the quench.

10:22.747 --> 10:24.707
[scraping]
<i>‐ It's hard as glass,</i>

10:24.707 --> 10:26.876
but there's a very slight warp,

10:26.876 --> 10:29.546
but I think I can take it out
on the grinder.

10:29.546 --> 10:32.298
And as I start to attack
this warp in the blade,

10:32.298 --> 10:36.427
<i>I notice the blade is curling</i>
<i>as it cools.</i>

10:36.427 --> 10:37.846
‐ Grant's got a big warp.

10:37.846 --> 10:39.514
That's not coming out
on the grinder.

10:39.514 --> 10:42.183
‐ I have to go back
into the forge.

10:42.183 --> 10:43.476
<i>Every time you quench it,</i>

10:43.476 --> 10:45.145
it's building massive stresses

10:45.145 --> 10:46.271
up in the steel.

10:46.271 --> 10:47.480
<i>You're running the risk</i>

10:47.480 --> 10:49.607
of having a huge fracture point.

10:49.607 --> 10:50.692
<i>But I have no choice.</i>

10:52.569 --> 10:54.946
‐ Here we go. Look out.
Look out.
‐ Moment of tr

10:54.946 --> 10:58.950
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:58.950 --> 11:00.326
‐ I pull it out,

11:00.326 --> 11:01.494
and the first thing I do now

11:01.494 --> 11:02.829
<i>is take it to the vise,</i>

11:02.829 --> 11:04.873
<i>and again, I get</i>
<i>that same issue.</i>

11:04.873 --> 11:06.875
It's curling right back
to where it was before.

11:06.875 --> 11:08.418
‐ You just hate to see somebody

11:08.418 --> 11:11.004
come this far along,
do a second quench,

11:11.004 --> 11:12.881
and something goes
terribly wrong.

11:12.881 --> 11:14.215
‐ Yeah, but he had no choice.

11:14.215 --> 11:16.676
That warp was not gonna come out
in the grinder.

11:16.676 --> 11:18.636
‐ I'm trying to fix this
in the vise,

11:18.636 --> 11:21.556
<i>and I did it to a degree,</i>

11:21.556 --> 11:23.391
but there's still a nasty warp
in there.

11:23.391 --> 11:26.352
I don't know what to do.

11:26.352 --> 11:29.355
<i>[hard rock riff]</i>

11:29.355 --> 11:31.733
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:31.733 --> 11:34.944
‐ Over here, we've got a quench
out of Colton.

11:34.944 --> 11:36.779
‐ I'm feeling pretty good
with this quench

11:36.779 --> 11:40.867
But my handle is a little bit
too narrow.

11:40.867 --> 11:43.077
‐ So Colton's handle
was a little bit long

11:43.077 --> 11:45.246
and really skinny
at the back end.

11:45.246 --> 11:47.415
Well, he just cut a piece
of that scrap steel.

11:47.415 --> 11:48.750
He's grinding a section
on the back

11:48.750 --> 11:50.376
of his handle right now.

11:50.376 --> 11:53.379
I think he's gonna weld on
just a little bit of flair.

11:53.379 --> 11:55.006
A really good idea
with that blade.

11:55.006 --> 11:56.633
‐ Nice.

11:58.801 --> 12:00.136
<i>So the junction of the handle,</i>

12:00.136 --> 12:02.347
it's too thin to keep
rolling with.

12:02.347 --> 12:03.806
It's not usable to me now.

12:03.806 --> 12:05.391
We're just gonna get rid of it.

12:05.391 --> 12:06.684
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:06.684 --> 12:08.102
I've still got enough spine.

12:08.102 --> 12:10.021
I've still got
a thick enough billet.

12:10.021 --> 12:13.274
I can draw this out
to my requirements.

12:13.274 --> 12:16.611
So at this point,
I've gotta quench.

12:16.611 --> 12:18.488
[low hissing]

12:18.488 --> 12:19.739
‐ Oh, y'all.

12:19.739 --> 12:21.991
That's a good‐looking blade.

12:21.991 --> 12:23.743
Nice, simple profile.

12:23.743 --> 12:25.703
‐ Nice, slight curve.
It's hard.

12:25.703 --> 12:27.080
<i>I would love to think</i>

12:27.080 --> 12:28.456
<i>that it's all downhill</i>
<i>from here on out,</i>

12:28.456 --> 12:29.707
but there's no way

12:29.707 --> 12:31.292
that I'm gonna treat it
like that.

12:31.292 --> 12:32.794
I could still screw up

12:32.794 --> 12:34.128
100 different ways.

12:34.128 --> 12:36.464
<i>[heavy metal bass riff]</i>

12:36.464 --> 12:38.049
<i>‐ As I'm grinding my blade,</i>

12:38.049 --> 12:40.134
I'm looking to make sure
if there's any cracks,

12:40.134 --> 12:41.886
any flaws in the blade.

12:41.886 --> 12:43.513
<i>I'm not seeing any at all,</i>

12:43.513 --> 12:46.808
but I'm worried that it might
be getting too thin.

12:46.808 --> 12:48.935
<i>They're gonna go as hard</i>
<i>as they can</i>

12:48.935 --> 12:51.479
on these blades to see
if they can produce any flaws,

12:51.479 --> 12:53.523
<i>and having it too thin,</i>

12:53.523 --> 12:54.649
<i>it might snap on me.</i>

12:54.649 --> 12:55.900
<i>It might shatter.</i>

12:55.900 --> 12:58.069
‐ Bryce is coming away
from the pantry

12:58.069 --> 13:00.238
with one of our gas torches,
here.

13:00.238 --> 13:02.782
‐ He's gonna try and blue back
the spine,

13:02.782 --> 13:03.825
but it would be a good idea

13:03.825 --> 13:05.243
to put some kind of heat sink

13:05.243 --> 13:06.953
so the heat doesn't travel
to your edge.

13:06.953 --> 13:08.663
You don't want a soft edge,

13:08.663 --> 13:10.290
especially on a chopper.

13:10.290 --> 13:14.335
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:14.335 --> 13:16.963
‐ At this point, the blade‐‐
it's ugly,

13:16.963 --> 13:19.632
and there's still a nasty warp
in there,

13:19.632 --> 13:21.676
<i>but I'm just trying to make</i>
<i>it functional.</i>

13:21.676 --> 13:24.220
‐ There are some deep, deep
hammer marks on Grant's blade.

13:24.220 --> 13:26.180
Man, that's a little alarming.

13:26.180 --> 13:27.807
‐ You can tell that Grant's
been trying

13:27.807 --> 13:29.642
to clean 'em up, 'cause he's
got grinder marks

13:29.642 --> 13:31.269
going all the way up
to the spine,

13:31.269 --> 13:33.855
but then you've got erratic
divots and dimples in it,

13:33.855 --> 13:35.315
and it just doesn't look good.

13:35.315 --> 13:37.817
<i>‐ I want that edge to be</i>
<i>a nice, even grind.</i>

13:37.817 --> 13:39.319
<i>I want it to be straight,</i>

13:39.319 --> 13:41.988
<i>and I want it to be easy</i>
<i>for me to sharpen later on</i>

13:41.988 --> 13:43.489
so that at the very least,

13:43.489 --> 13:45.950
I have a blade
that can be considered working.

13:45.950 --> 13:46.951
[sighs]

13:46.951 --> 13:48.411
<i>It's not gonna be pretty,</i>

13:48.411 --> 13:50.913
but it might get the job done.
[chuckles]

13:50.913 --> 13:53.249
[grinding]

13:53.249 --> 13:56.335
‐ Five! Four! Three!

13:56.335 --> 13:58.004
Two! One!

13:58.004 --> 13:59.464
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines!

13:59.464 --> 14:00.673
Drop your tools!

14:00.673 --> 14:04.135
This first round
of competition is over!

14:04.135 --> 14:06.471
<i>‐ I'm thinking about if</i>
<i>the judges like my blade.</i>

14:06.471 --> 14:07.889
<i>I hope there's nothing</i>
<i>for them</i>

14:07.889 --> 14:08.890
to pick out about it.

14:08.890 --> 14:10.349
<i>And then my thought changes</i>

14:10.349 --> 14:12.894
<i>to "You just turned</i>
<i>this 16‐inch piston</i>

14:12.894 --> 14:15.980
"into a knife that is in total,
19 inches long.

14:15.980 --> 14:17.273
"You should be proud of
yourself

14:17.273 --> 14:18.649
<i>"in what you just produced.</i>

14:18.649 --> 14:21.444
The knife looks great,
so smile."

14:21.444 --> 14:22.445
[chuckles]

14:22.445 --> 14:24.530
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

14:24.530 --> 14:27.450
‐ Bladesmiths, in this
first round of competition,

14:27.450 --> 14:29.368
you guys worked like a team
of surgeons

14:29.368 --> 14:32.121
to rip the beating heart
out of Big Blu

14:32.121 --> 14:33.498
and create signature choppers

14:33.498 --> 14:35.083
between 11 and 13 inches,

14:35.083 --> 14:36.959
and now it's time
for your critiques.

14:36.959 --> 14:38.461
Colton, you're up first.

14:38.461 --> 14:40.546
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:40.546 --> 14:42.715
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:42.715 --> 14:44.592
<i>‐ I like this profile.</i>
<i>It's really nice.</i>

14:44.592 --> 14:46.552
<i>It's clean.</i>
<i>It's a good shape.</i>

14:46.552 --> 14:49.430
There's a little bit of a warp
in the tang.

14:49.430 --> 14:51.224
<i>Kicks a little bit to one side.</i>

14:51.224 --> 14:52.934
This is a really
good‐looking knife.

14:52.934 --> 14:54.811
I'd love to see it
just dialed in,

14:54.811 --> 14:56.896
but you're well on your way.
Good job.

14:56.896 --> 14:58.397
‐ All right, Bryce!

14:58.397 --> 15:00.691
You're up. Please present
your blade to the judges.

15:00.691 --> 15:03.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:03.486 --> 15:04.737
<i>‐ All right, Bryce.</i>

15:04.737 --> 15:06.072
<i>From the looks of your blade,</i>

15:06.072 --> 15:08.032
<i>it has a big butt end,</i>

15:08.032 --> 15:09.450
I cannot lie.

15:09.450 --> 15:11.619
[David chuckles]

15:11.619 --> 15:13.579
It actually works right there.

15:13.579 --> 15:15.331
Just be careful,
if you move on,

15:15.331 --> 15:17.333
when you start putting
the scales on this,

15:17.333 --> 15:19.752
that it maintains that good fit
in the hand.

15:19.752 --> 15:21.420
Now, your blade from the spine

15:21.420 --> 15:22.630
already tapers to the tip,

15:22.630 --> 15:24.215
<i>but you have all these issues</i>

15:24.215 --> 15:25.550
<i>that you have to fix here</i>

15:25.550 --> 15:26.926
<i>to try to clean that up.</i>

15:26.926 --> 15:28.761
Overall, good job.

15:28.761 --> 15:29.971
‐ Thank you.

15:29.971 --> 15:31.222
‐ All right, Grant.
You're up.

15:31.222 --> 15:33.224
Present your blade
to the judges.

15:33.224 --> 15:35.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:35.601 --> 15:38.771
‐ All right, so you've got
this big warp.

15:38.771 --> 15:40.064
It sits right in there.

15:40.064 --> 15:41.440
And that's a huge divot

15:41.440 --> 15:42.775
on the back of your blade.

15:42.775 --> 15:45.778
Scale‐wise,
having that extra space,

15:45.778 --> 15:47.989
what winds up happening
is you have to make a decision

15:47.989 --> 15:49.532
on where you want
to put your hand

15:49.532 --> 15:50.783
as opposed to having it

15:50.783 --> 15:52.118
comfortably sitting
in your hand.

15:52.118 --> 15:54.287
So if you move forward,
deal with the warp.

15:54.287 --> 15:55.830
Maybe there's something
you can do

15:55.830 --> 15:57.790
with this handle
to make it more functional

15:57.790 --> 15:59.750
for a chopper.

15:59.750 --> 16:02.545
‐ And the old dog in the pack
of young, hungry wolves.

16:02.545 --> 16:03.796
All right, Craig.

16:03.796 --> 16:05.506
Present your blade
to the judges.

16:05.506 --> 16:08.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:08.301 --> 16:09.969
<i>‐ There's a lot I like</i>
<i>about this, Craig.</i>

16:09.969 --> 16:11.220
<i>It's straight.</i>

16:11.220 --> 16:12.889
<i>You've got enough meat</i>
<i>up here</i>

16:12.889 --> 16:14.807
where you still got room
to work.

16:14.807 --> 16:17.685
Your handle? Mostly there.

16:17.685 --> 16:20.146
<i>What started out looking</i>
<i>like a finger weld,</i>

16:20.146 --> 16:21.814
now, it's like, big enough
for two fingers, now.

16:21.814 --> 16:23.191
It's definitely workable.

16:23.191 --> 16:24.400
Just be careful you don't get

16:24.400 --> 16:25.943
too thin back here.

16:25.943 --> 16:28.863
But otherwise, good job.
‐ Thank you.

16:28.863 --> 16:30.489
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

16:30.489 --> 16:31.824
‐ All right, gentlemen.

16:31.824 --> 16:33.910
The judges' deliberation
is complete.

16:33.910 --> 16:36.871
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

16:36.871 --> 16:40.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:40.833 --> 16:42.001
Grant.

16:42.001 --> 16:43.711
Your blade didn't make the cut.

16:43.711 --> 16:47.006
‐ Grant, your blade
has the most pronounced warp.

16:47.006 --> 16:49.425
<i>That, coupled with the divot</i>
<i>on the spine</i>

16:49.425 --> 16:52.595
<i>and a less‐than‐desirable</i>
<i>handle scale end design,</i>

16:52.595 --> 16:55.514
is the reason
we're sending you home.

16:55.514 --> 16:57.683
‐ Grant, unfortunately today,

16:57.683 --> 17:00.019
I have to ask you
to please surrender your blade.

17:00.019 --> 17:01.187
<i>[mournful instrumental music]</i>

17:01.187 --> 17:02.855
<i>‐ I could kind of</i>
<i>see this coming,</i>

17:02.855 --> 17:03.856
<i>once I finished my blade.</i>

17:03.856 --> 17:05.024
I knew the issues with it.

17:05.024 --> 17:06.192
[whispered]
Thank you.

17:06.192 --> 17:07.777
<i>I definitely think</i>
<i>I got in trouble</i>

17:07.777 --> 17:09.278
<i>just getting bogged down</i>
<i>in the forging,</i>

17:09.278 --> 17:11.113
and then the warp in the quench

17:11.113 --> 17:13.074
<i>was really the nail</i>
<i>in the coffin.</i>

17:13.074 --> 17:15.034
<i>I'm going back</i>
<i>to the drawing board.</i>

17:15.034 --> 17:16.619
I'm gonna address
some of the issues

17:16.619 --> 17:17.995
<i>I saw in my work, here.</i>

17:17.995 --> 17:21.540
Gonna try and make
a competition chopper.

17:21.540 --> 17:23.209
<i>See if I can do it</i>
<i>in my own home forge,</i>

17:23.209 --> 17:25.795
so that I know I can best
this challenge.

17:25.795 --> 17:28.756
<i>[intense music]</i>

17:28.756 --> 17:30.049
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:30.049 --> 17:31.926
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

17:31.926 --> 17:33.094
You've made it
to the second round

17:33.094 --> 17:34.387
of this competition.

17:34.387 --> 17:36.055
And now that those blades
have been tempered,

17:36.055 --> 17:37.098
it's time to turn them

17:37.098 --> 17:38.558
into fully functional choppers

17:38.558 --> 17:40.309
by attaching handles to them.

17:40.309 --> 17:43.062
You'll have just two hours
in which to complete your work.

17:43.062 --> 17:45.231
This is an homage to Big Blu,

17:45.231 --> 17:48.693
so you must incorporate
blue handle material

17:48.693 --> 17:50.736
into your handle's
finished construction.

17:50.736 --> 17:52.613
Pay a little respect
to that machine

17:52.613 --> 17:54.699
that's helped all the champions
before you.

17:54.699 --> 17:56.284
At the end of this round,

17:56.284 --> 17:58.452
we'll test your blades
for strength and durability

17:58.452 --> 18:00.288
in that bamboo chop,

18:00.288 --> 18:03.874
and for edge retention
in the rope bridge slice.

18:03.874 --> 18:05.167
Good luck, bladesmiths.

18:05.167 --> 18:06.669
Your time starts now.

18:06.669 --> 18:07.920
<i>[energetic rock music]</i>

18:07.920 --> 18:10.506
All right, so two hours
on the clock.

18:10.506 --> 18:11.757
Given, we've got some problems
out there

18:11.757 --> 18:13.092
on The Forge floor.

18:13.092 --> 18:14.260
‐ Colton's bound determined

18:14.260 --> 18:16.053
to get that blade straight.

18:16.053 --> 18:17.847
<i>‐ The judge's main concern</i>
<i>with my blade</i>

18:17.847 --> 18:20.266
<i>is that there is a little,</i>
<i>tiny warp,</i>

18:20.266 --> 18:21.517
and I did not see that

18:21.517 --> 18:23.477
in the previous round,

18:23.477 --> 18:25.771
<i>but if I take a 400‐grit belt,</i>

18:25.771 --> 18:28.107
<i>it shouldn't take that long</i>
<i>to get it out.</i>

18:28.107 --> 18:29.900
<i>I'm feeling a little bit</i>
<i>more pressure</i>

18:29.900 --> 18:31.986
than round one,
because I have less time.

18:31.986 --> 18:35.448
But overall, I still feel
pretty confident.

18:35.448 --> 18:38.117
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:38.117 --> 18:39.285
‐ Testing handle material.

18:39.285 --> 18:40.369
‐ Did he throw it
on the floor?

18:40.369 --> 18:42.121
‐ Yes, he did.
‐ Did he?

18:42.121 --> 18:43.789
‐ Yeah, he did. Yeah, he did.
‐ Nice. Good job, kid.

18:43.789 --> 18:45.249
That's what I like to see.

18:45.249 --> 18:47.543
Throw it on the ground!
See if it breaks.

18:47.543 --> 18:49.378
<i>‐ After getting</i>
<i>my handle material,</i>

18:49.378 --> 18:51.130
<i>I know I need to be camped out</i>
<i>at the grinder.</i>

18:51.130 --> 18:53.007
I want to make sure that blade
is nice and smooth,

18:53.007 --> 18:54.550
so it has a nice cut

18:54.550 --> 18:56.135
<i>when it goes</i>
<i>through the challenges.</i>

18:56.135 --> 18:58.304
How would you go about getting
that warp out right there?

18:58.304 --> 18:59.639
It's just like an edge,
you know?

18:59.639 --> 19:01.140
‐ Uh, just grind it.
‐ I would just grind it?

19:01.140 --> 19:02.266
‐ Grind 'em good.

19:02.266 --> 19:03.476
‐ I think I'm most worried

19:03.476 --> 19:06.312
about what Bryce is doing
over there.

19:06.312 --> 19:09.065
I'm seeing a lot of erratic,
back‐and‐forth movement

19:09.065 --> 19:10.858
against the 8‐inch
contact wheel.

19:10.858 --> 19:12.985
‐ It's just erratic grinding.

19:12.985 --> 19:14.236
<i>He's not staying flat</i>
<i>on there.</i>

19:14.236 --> 19:15.529
<i>He's not making smooth passes.</i>

19:15.529 --> 19:17.490
He's just kind of going
all over the place.

19:17.490 --> 19:20.951
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:20.951 --> 19:23.204
‐ Now, Craig's got
the straightest,

19:23.204 --> 19:25.539
nicest blade coming out
of round one.

19:25.539 --> 19:26.999
‐ I agree.

19:26.999 --> 19:28.668
See the way the light reflects
off of Craig's blade?

19:28.668 --> 19:29.710
‐ Yes.

19:29.710 --> 19:30.961
‐ It reflects evenly.
‐ Yes.

19:30.961 --> 19:32.630
‐ And that's what you want
to see.

19:32.630 --> 19:34.590
‐ Right, you could, like,
signal an aircraft with that.

19:34.590 --> 19:35.758
‐ Exactly.

19:35.758 --> 19:37.176
‐ Overall, he's got
a very nice design

19:37.176 --> 19:38.552
for his chopper that he has.

19:38.552 --> 19:40.179
You got some whoop‐de‐dos
on the handle.

19:40.179 --> 19:41.389
Refine that.

19:41.389 --> 19:42.682
<i>‐ The judges thought</i>
<i>everything</i>

19:42.682 --> 19:44.183
<i>was pretty good except</i>
<i>for the handle.</i>

19:44.183 --> 19:45.893
And they said it just wasn't
quite there yet.

19:45.893 --> 19:48.437
<i>There was a finger weld</i>
<i>that had widened out</i>

19:48.437 --> 19:50.523
<i>just a little bit more</i>
<i>than they would prefer.</i>

19:50.523 --> 19:52.400
So what I'm gonna do
is draw that out,

19:52.400 --> 19:53.818
round it off, and make it more

19:53.818 --> 19:55.069
into a palm swell.

19:55.069 --> 19:56.320
<i>I do not want to go home</i>

19:56.320 --> 19:57.613
<i>because of a bad handle.</i>

19:57.613 --> 20:00.783
‐ Colton has got some epoxy
ready to go,

20:00.783 --> 20:04.370
and it looks like he's
fitting up his handle scales.

20:04.370 --> 20:07.164
<i>‐ I get ready to put the tang</i>
<i>right on there,</i>

20:07.164 --> 20:09.417
and then I realize that
I forgot

20:09.417 --> 20:12.628
<i>to pre‐grind the part</i>
<i>of the handle scales</i>

20:12.628 --> 20:14.130
<i>that's gonna be actually</i>

20:14.130 --> 20:16.006
on the blade‐side
of the tang.

20:16.006 --> 20:18.217
If you don't pre‐grind
the handle scales,

