I thought it went well,

32:09.928 --> 32:12.097
<i>but when I go in and take</i>
<i>a second look at it,</i>

32:12.097 --> 32:13.932
<i>a warp has appeared.</i>

32:13.932 --> 32:16.226
If this bow isn't symmetrical
exactly,

32:16.226 --> 32:18.478
it could cause the rock
to fly

32:18.478 --> 32:21.064
at an unpredictable trajectory.

32:23.066 --> 32:25.610
<i>So tomorrow, I'm gonna have</i>
<i>to fix it,</i>

32:25.610 --> 32:27.237
<i>one way or another.</i>

32:27.237 --> 32:28.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:28.572 --> 32:30.115
<i>‐ It's the start of day two,</i>

32:30.115 --> 32:31.449
<i>and the first thing I'm</i>
<i>thinking about working on</i>

32:31.449 --> 32:34.244
<i>today is probably getting my</i>
<i>stock cut down</i>

32:34.244 --> 32:35.912
<i>so I can kind of visualize</i>

32:35.912 --> 32:37.497
how some of my pieces
need to look

32:37.497 --> 32:39.457
and how they need to fall
into it.

32:39.457 --> 32:40.917
[machinery whirring]

32:40.917 --> 32:42.836
<i>So now I'm doing a lot</i>
<i>of finer fitting,</i>

32:42.836 --> 32:44.629
marrying up the trigger
to the release.

32:44.629 --> 32:46.047
<i>Things like that.</i>

32:46.047 --> 32:47.549
I'll have to fine‐tune
a little bit more.

32:47.549 --> 32:49.134
That's fine, but for now,

32:49.134 --> 32:51.761
everything's starting
to fit together as a whole.

32:51.761 --> 32:54.681
<i>[upbeat funk music]</i>

32:54.681 --> 32:57.142
<i>‐ So it's day two,</i>
<i>and my plan today</i>

32:57.142 --> 32:59.394
<i>is to refine the bow.</i>

32:59.394 --> 33:01.813
<i>The quench yesterday</i>
<i>did warp it a little bit,</i>

33:01.813 --> 33:03.523
<i>so I'm gonna have</i>
<i>to fix that today.</i>

33:03.523 --> 33:05.108
[harsh grinding]

33:05.108 --> 33:07.277
As I start grinding,
and I'm looking at the warp,

33:07.277 --> 33:09.446
I'm realizing that
it's not gonna be too hard

33:09.446 --> 33:11.990
<i>to get this warp out of there.</i>

33:11.990 --> 33:14.492
So after the bow and the string
are complete,

33:14.492 --> 33:16.828
<i>I move on to adjusting</i>
<i>the struts</i>

33:16.828 --> 33:20.123
<i>and friction‐fitting the bow</i>
<i>to the stock.</i>

33:20.123 --> 33:21.791
<i>The thing I'm worried</i>
<i>about most</i>

33:21.791 --> 33:25.462
<i>in the construction</i>
<i>is making the trigger precise</i>

33:25.462 --> 33:28.798
<i>and making the draw weight</i>
<i>not too heavy,</i>

33:28.798 --> 33:30.175
<i>but not too light as well.</i>

33:30.175 --> 33:32.344
<i>The trigger</i>
<i>on this rock‐throwing crossbow</i>

33:32.344 --> 33:35.180
<i>is made to basically hold</i>
<i>a little loop</i>

33:35.180 --> 33:36.806
<i>on the back of a pouch,</i>

33:36.806 --> 33:39.476
<i>rather than release a string</i>
<i>with an arrow.</i>

33:39.476 --> 33:42.187
I finished all
of the metal parts,

33:42.187 --> 33:45.857
<i>and I also finished up</i>
<i>the stock.</i>

33:45.857 --> 33:48.360
<i>[hard rock guitar riff]</i>

33:48.360 --> 33:49.653
<i>‐ Start of day three,</i>

33:49.653 --> 33:50.862
<i>I've still got a lot</i>
<i>of work to do.</i>

33:50.862 --> 33:52.072
[sander buzzing]

33:52.072 --> 33:53.615
Doing a little bit more work
on the stock

33:53.615 --> 33:54.866
<i>and pushing the thing</i>

33:54.866 --> 33:56.368
<i>towards being closer</i>
<i>to finished.</i>

33:56.368 --> 33:57.827
So if you watch here,

33:57.827 --> 34:00.455
you can see if I put
forward pressure on this,

34:00.455 --> 34:02.040
it's locked in,

34:02.040 --> 34:04.334
and once I hit the trigger,
it falls forward,

34:04.334 --> 34:07.545
and that would be the string
being released.

34:07.545 --> 34:10.048
I made the trigger on the bow
to be relatively light

34:10.048 --> 34:11.841
<i>to aid in accuracy</i>
<i>on the weapon.</i>

34:11.841 --> 34:13.760
<i>The less pressure you have</i>
<i>to put on the trigger,</i>

34:13.760 --> 34:15.345
<i>the easier it is</i>
<i>to discharge it.</i>

34:15.345 --> 34:17.305
Got all the furniture
put on there,

34:17.305 --> 34:20.558
<i>but otherwise, I mean,</i>
<i>it's mocked up on the bow.</i>

34:20.558 --> 34:22.227
<i>I got a lot of refinement</i>
<i>to do,</i>

34:22.227 --> 34:23.895
<i>so I'm ready.</i>

34:23.895 --> 34:25.814
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:25.814 --> 34:27.315
<i>‐ So today is day four,</i>

34:27.315 --> 34:30.026
<i>and at this point,</i>
<i>the crossbow is functional,</i>

34:30.026 --> 34:32.696
<i>but still needs to be aimed</i>
<i>and sighted in perfectly.</i>

34:32.696 --> 34:34.197
<i>I'm gonna set up a target</i>

34:34.197 --> 34:37.534
and monitor where it hits
and how accurate it is.

34:37.534 --> 34:40.578
<i>It's pretty lightweight,</i>
<i>and it's easy to wield.</i>

34:40.578 --> 34:42.956
Craig, I've got the
"Forged in Fire" championship

34:42.956 --> 34:47.711
in my sights, and I'm gonna
be hitting my target.

34:47.711 --> 34:50.714
<i>[intense music]</i>

34:50.714 --> 34:54.759
<i>♪</i> ♪

34:54.759 --> 34:57.429
‐ Colton, Craig, welcome back
to The Forge.

34:57.429 --> 34:59.639
You fellas have had four days
at your home forges

34:59.639 --> 35:02.767
to work on your rock‐throwing
crossbows.

35:02.767 --> 35:04.436
Colton, how did it go?

35:04.436 --> 35:05.729
‐ It went really good.

35:05.729 --> 35:07.397
<i>[smooth funk music]</i>

35:07.397 --> 35:09.107
<i>All the metal parts on it</i>

35:09.107 --> 35:11.234
<i>except for the prod</i>
<i>are mild steel.</i>

35:11.234 --> 35:12.485
<i>The stock is made</i>
<i>out of wood,</i>

35:12.485 --> 35:14.779
<i>and the prod is 5160.</i>

35:14.779 --> 35:16.615
‐ All right.
Craig, how'd it go for you?

35:16.615 --> 35:18.116
‐ It threw a couple
of curveballs at me,

35:18.116 --> 35:20.243
but I think it came out
pretty well in the end.

35:20.243 --> 35:21.620
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:21.620 --> 35:24.664
<i>The prod? It weighs out</i>
<i>at about 90 pounds.</i>

35:24.664 --> 35:26.374
<i>It's 80CRV2.</i>

35:26.374 --> 35:27.500
<i>The stock is white oak.</i>

35:27.500 --> 35:29.085
<i>The pommel is mahogany,</i>

35:29.085 --> 35:30.503
<i>and everything else</i>
<i>is mild steel.</i>

35:30.503 --> 35:31.963
‐ All right, I hope
she's strong enough

35:31.963 --> 35:34.591
to be the "Forged in Fire"
champion for both of you,

35:34.591 --> 35:37.135
because coming up
are our weapons tests.

35:37.135 --> 35:39.471
Up first, the KEAL test.
Doug?

35:39.471 --> 35:42.432
<i>[intense drumming]</i>

35:42.432 --> 35:43.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:43.516 --> 35:45.644
‐ All right, weapon smiths,

35:45.644 --> 35:47.604
welcome to the KEAL test.

35:47.604 --> 35:49.564
Encased in this ballistics gel

35:49.564 --> 35:50.774
is a mock heart.

35:50.774 --> 35:52.275
I'm gonna attempt three times

35:52.275 --> 35:54.194
to be able to pierce the heart
that's in it.

35:54.194 --> 35:55.737
Colton, you're up first.
You ready for this?

35:55.737 --> 35:57.447
‐ Yeah.
‐ Let's do this.

35:57.447 --> 35:59.199
<i>[quiet, tense music]</i>

35:59.199 --> 36:00.325
<i>‐ Coming into testing,</i>

36:00.325 --> 36:01.493
my biggest fear is that

36:01.493 --> 36:03.161
it's not gonna be strong
enough.

36:03.161 --> 36:05.121
<i>[music gains intensity]</i>

36:05.121 --> 36:07.582
[breathes nervously]

36:07.582 --> 36:09.292
[trigger clicks]

36:09.292 --> 36:12.754
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:12.754 --> 36:14.839
[trigger clicks]

36:14.839 --> 36:16.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:16.466 --> 36:19.511
[trigger clicks
and gel squelches]

36:20.470 --> 36:22.681
<i>[quiet, tense music]</i>

36:22.681 --> 36:24.099
‐ All right, Colton.

36:24.099 --> 36:26.476
Let's talk about
your rock‐throwing crossbow.

36:26.476 --> 36:29.479
First up, it seems to be
very sturdy.

36:29.479 --> 36:32.524
I like that it's spring‐loaded
right here on the trigger.

36:32.524 --> 36:34.651
It's got a nice weight to it.

36:34.651 --> 36:36.653
Now, it was easy
to auto‐correct.

36:36.653 --> 36:39.698
After the first shot,
I pretty much sighted it

36:39.698 --> 36:41.116
right and straight,
dead‐center.

36:41.116 --> 36:43.326
Both times with the shots
in there,

36:43.326 --> 36:45.328
it didn't penetrate
into the heart

36:45.328 --> 36:48.373
but hit the target right
in front of the heart.

36:48.373 --> 36:49.624
Overall, sir,

36:49.624 --> 36:53.002
this should KEAL.

36:53.002 --> 36:54.713
All right, Craig.
It's your turn.

36:54.713 --> 36:56.381
Are you ready, sir?
‐ Yes, I am.

36:56.381 --> 36:57.382
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:57.382 --> 36:58.883
<i>After seeing Colton's,</i>

36:58.883 --> 37:01.219
I know his prod is lighter
than mine.

37:01.219 --> 37:02.846
<i>I know it's not got</i>
<i>the velocity,</i>

37:02.846 --> 37:05.098
and if his penetrated deep
enough to touch that heart,

37:05.098 --> 37:06.683
I'm gonna be inside of it.

37:06.683 --> 37:09.686
<i>[music gaining intensity]</i>

37:09.686 --> 37:11.229
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:11.229 --> 37:12.897
[trigger clicks]

37:12.897 --> 37:14.858
<i>[heavy metal guitar riff]</i>

37:14.858 --> 37:18.236
[trigger clicks
and gel squelches]

37:18.236 --> 37:19.612
[whispered]
Yeah.

37:19.612 --> 37:20.947
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:20.947 --> 37:24.576
[trigger clicks
and gel squelches]

37:24.576 --> 37:26.745
Did it hit it?
‐ I don't know.

37:29.372 --> 37:31.499
‐ Ta‐da!

37:31.499 --> 37:33.543
‐ Yes!

37:33.543 --> 37:34.961
‐ All right, Craig.

37:34.961 --> 37:37.422
So it's definitely
a more powerful crossbow

37:37.422 --> 37:39.090
that you have here.

37:39.090 --> 37:41.426
The thing about this
is that the sights

37:41.426 --> 37:43.720
that you have on there
is dead‐center.

37:43.720 --> 37:45.889
After the first shot,
aimed a little bit low,

37:45.889 --> 37:48.933
adjusted for it,
it's dead‐on center.

37:48.933 --> 37:51.311
Second one, ricocheted
to the side of the heart,

37:51.311 --> 37:55.064
<i>and on the third one,</i>
<i>it went through the heart.</i>

37:55.064 --> 37:57.734
You weapon, sir,
will KEAL.

37:57.734 --> 38:00.361
‐ Yeah, it will.
[chuckles]

38:00.361 --> 38:03.615
<i>[intense music]</i>

38:03.615 --> 38:04.783
‐ All right, gentlemen.

38:04.783 --> 38:06.910
It's time for the impact test.

38:06.910 --> 38:08.620
To test your bows,
I'll be firing them

38:08.620 --> 38:10.747
into our tempered glass, here.

38:10.747 --> 38:13.082
The idea, of course,
is to shatter that glass.

38:13.082 --> 38:14.542
Colton, you're up.
Are you ready?

38:14.542 --> 38:16.503
‐ Do it.

38:16.503 --> 38:17.587
<i>So I know that Craig's bow</i>

38:17.587 --> 38:18.963
is more powerful than mine,

38:18.963 --> 38:20.965
and it beat me in the KEAL test

38:20.965 --> 38:22.258
<i>because it went right</i>
<i>into the heart,</i>

38:24.886 --> 38:29.015
‐ I definitely need to perform
very well in this impact test,
so I'm thinking
I definitely need to p

38:29.015 --> 38:32.894
or I'm pretty sure
I'm going home.

38:32.894 --> 38:35.021
[trigger clicks]

38:35.021 --> 38:38.233
[glass explodes]

38:38.233 --> 38:39.317
‐ [laughs]

38:39.317 --> 38:40.819
‐ All right, Colton.

38:40.819 --> 38:42.904
The craftsmanship that went
into this weapon

38:42.904 --> 38:44.656
is really beautiful.

38:44.656 --> 38:47.325
I like the trigger system
you've got here, the catch,

38:47.325 --> 38:49.118
the way you've got
the stop pins

38:49.118 --> 38:50.995
for it to keep it centered.

38:50.995 --> 38:52.580
I like that you've got
the spring in there

38:52.580 --> 38:56.000
to keep that handle
in a lock position.

38:56.000 --> 38:58.461
I like the way you put
this secondary leaf

38:58.461 --> 39:00.171
on the bow up there,
that's very clever.

39:00.171 --> 39:03.091
It doesn't have that strong
of draw weight,

39:03.091 --> 39:05.176
but certainly, it hits
with enough force

39:05.176 --> 39:06.302
to break that glass.

39:06.302 --> 39:09.013
Well done. Nice piece.
‐ Thank you.

39:09.013 --> 39:10.390
‐ All right, Craig. You're up.
You ready?

39:10.390 --> 39:12.016
‐ Oh, absolutely.
‐ Okay.

39:12.016 --> 39:15.019
<i>[intense percussive music]</i>

39:15.019 --> 39:22.026
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:25.864 --> 39:27.699
<i>[uncertain notes]</i>

39:27.699 --> 39:29.200
[whispered]
‐ That's a problem.

39:29.200 --> 39:30.493
‐ Did he touch the trigger?

39:30.493 --> 39:31.703
‐ I don't know that he did.

39:31.703 --> 39:32.871
I think it slipped.

39:32.871 --> 39:36.708
<i>[foreboding drumming music]</i>

39:36.708 --> 39:38.376
‐ Craig, we've got
a problem.

39:38.376 --> 39:40.253
I never touched the trigger.

39:40.253 --> 39:42.839
‐ [sighs deeply]

39:42.839 --> 39:45.133
<i>Well, it would appear</i>
<i>that I just had</i>

39:45.133 --> 39:46.759
an accidental discharge,

39:46.759 --> 39:49.804
and that might have just
lost it for me.

39:49.804 --> 39:52.223
‐ Doesn't take anything
to release that.

39:52.223 --> 39:53.641
<i>‐ Now I made the trigger</i>
<i>on the bow</i>

39:53.641 --> 39:55.393
<i>to be relatively light.</i>

39:55.393 --> 39:57.103
Maybe I made it too light.

39:57.103 --> 40:00.356
Either way, that presents
a danger to everybody.

40:00.356 --> 40:03.276
<i>[pensive electronic music]</i>

40:03.276 --> 40:04.736
‐ All right, Craig,

40:04.736 --> 40:07.322
something very serious happened
here on The Forge floor.

40:07.322 --> 40:09.407
We had an accidental discharge
with your weapon.

40:09.407 --> 40:11.409
Dave Baker never touched
that trigger.

40:11.409 --> 40:12.577
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:12.577 --> 40:14.078
[bow releases
and glass shatters]

40:14.078 --> 40:16.748
This is a mechanical
malfunction,

40:16.748 --> 40:18.041
and after reviewing
the construction

40:18.041 --> 40:19.250
of your crossbow,

40:19.250 --> 40:20.960
the hook you made
wasn't large enough

40:20.960 --> 40:22.962
<i>to hold the high‐tension</i>
<i>string securely,</i>

40:22.962 --> 40:25.256
creating a hair trigger,
and that results

40:25.256 --> 40:29.344
in a very dangerous
and unpredictable weapon

40:29.344 --> 40:32.472
and has earned your weapon
a vote of no confidence.

40:32.472 --> 40:34.766
And for that reason,
we cannot continue testing.

40:34.766 --> 40:36.809
I'd like to invite you
to shake my hand,

40:36.809 --> 40:38.728
shake the judges' hands,

40:38.728 --> 40:41.606
and please leave The Forge.

40:41.606 --> 40:45.151
‐ I completely support
the judges' decision.

40:45.151 --> 40:47.487
‐ A powerful weapon‐‐I just
wish that trigger were safer.

40:47.487 --> 40:49.948
‐ I took a calculated risk
to aid in accuracy,

40:49.948 --> 40:51.950
and it turned around
and bit me.

40:51.950 --> 40:54.619
<i>I never made a stone‐throwing</i>
<i>crossbow before,</i>

40:54.619 --> 40:56.287
so I don't have any regrets.

40:56.287 --> 40:59.624
I still won, I'm just not
getting paid for it. [chuckles]

40:59.624 --> 41:03.127
<i>[intense music]</i>

41:03.127 --> 41:05.505
‐ Colton, strength and power

41:05.505 --> 41:07.674
matter when we talk
about any weapon,

41:07.674 --> 41:11.344
but so do precision,
manufacturing, and safety.

41:11.344 --> 41:13.763
You, sir, are
the "Forged in Fire" champion

41:13.763 --> 41:15.640
and that's a title
that comes with a check

41:15.640 --> 41:17.433
for $10,000.
Good job, brother.

41:17.433 --> 41:20.311
[judges applaud]

41:20.311 --> 41:22.063
How do you feel right now?

41:22.063 --> 41:23.439
‐ Amazing. I can't believe it.

41:23.439 --> 41:24.983
